text: At the source: pours amber with a white head. Aroma is caramel and malty and the like. Taste is sweet. Low hoppiness. Some bread. Simple and what it should be.
Draft. Lively, hoppy aroma with lively carbonation. Very well balanced beer, medium dry with hop and malt flavors. Slightly bitter finish. Very drinkable by itself or with food.

4 oz draft pour at Iron Hill Newark. Thanks to my friend Mike for the taste. Golden brown with off-white head. Aromas of sweet fruit, caramel, light herb. Tastes of sweet fruit, malt, caramel. Medium body with a dry finish.
on tap at Maple Shade - a pretty good Oktoberfest . Its definitely drinkable. Not too sweet (which is an issue with some of these). Good brew.
On draft at Iron Hill Voorhees. Poured a clear golden orange color with a small foamy white head. Aroma and taste are much the same. Sweet grain, caramel, lemon, yeast, and slight booziness

Tap at Lancaster, this one only 4.5% abv. Dark orange-copper with no head, nose is sweet with candy/icing sweetness and a touch of apple. Taste light-medium bitter, touch soapy; simple medium body with touch of rye-like spice, earth. Malt-forward.
Draft. Crystal clear golden amber color, white edge head. Aroma of caramel biscuit. Taste is fruity caramel.

Tap at Voorhees. Pours clear amber with a small, fizzy white head, short retention with light lacing. Aroma is toast and caramel malt, earthy hops. Flavor is malt and hop balanced with a clean lager character and a sweet finish. Medium body and carbonation.

Growler pour, courtesy of Pedro, from West Chester. Pours a fairly clean amber with dense off-white head and seafoam lacing. Nose of bread, caramel, nut. Sweet up front with a dry finish with a little more bitterness than a typical for the style. Medium body.
Pours amber with a tan head.  Aroma is toast, nutty, caramel and earthy.  Taste is sweet all the way through.  Light bodied and very smooth textured.

DeeP amber thin off-white head; not much aroma; Flava is nice and rich and complex blend of malt, slightly roasted and hops and alcohOl; feels ri ch with a nice biting fizz.  Finishes long and dry some grassy notes.Earlier Rating: 9/25/2012 Total Score: 3Flava and finish is the strong suit.  Which is good for drinking a beer.  Hint of toasty nutty in aroma but nice and powerful in the Flava.  Finishes slightly sweet yet bitter and dry.

Tap at Maple Shade. Pours out an attractive orange color with a small off white head. Aroma is of caramel malts, grainy bread, mild honey and some lingering floral hops in the background. Taste is much the same, clean caramel, grains, cereal, grass, bread, some honey and a light lingering bitterness on the finish.

On tap at Chestnut Hill.  Clear, dark amber, no head.  Toasted caramel malt nose.  Malty sweet with some roastiness.  Hops mix with roastiness to provide some bitterness but this is primarily a malt profile.
A nice version of the style. Malty with bread, caramel, some yeast. The flavor is the same, nicely balanced, and good with the Oktoberfest menu.

Pours a light coffee color with a light tan head and a little lace.  Aroma is of chocolate, coffee, caramel and roasted malts.  Roasted malts, peat, a little dark chocolate and resin.  Kind of sour with a clean, bitter finish.

Pours a dark amber with a medium tan head...nice lacing.  Aroma has some roastiness and nuttiness...bready as billed.  Flavor follows suit and has nice earthy notes...faint spice and bitterness in the back end.  Mouthfeel is lively and refreshing with a dry bitter/roasty finish.

(Wilmington, 6.8% ABV)  Off-white head atop clear dark amber body.  Aroma is moderately sweet, caramel, some cherry, light earthy.  Taste is moderately sweet, caramel, cherry, light earthy, lager yeast.  Light-medium body, light stickiness.  Not very Oktoberfesty, but tasty.

On tap at Wilmington brewpub.  Pours a clear copper color with a one finger of frothy off white head wich leaves some lacing.  The aroma is sweet bready malts with spicy hops.  The taste is intially sweet, with a big breadiness that is balanced with some spicy drying bitterness, which gives this a very smooth finish. The mouthfeel is medium and crisp, with moderate carbonation.

On tap @ maple shade. Pours a clear amber brown with a small beigh head. Aroma was bready malts, faint caramel and had some floral notes. Flavor was clean smooth and slightly sweet with toasted mal;ts, bread, light caramel and some nuttiness.

Growler courtesy of my friend J, filled at the Lancaster, PA location.  Pours a clear golden brown with a moderate tan head that lasted through the first quarter of the glass and left ample spotty lace.  Pleasant aroma of malt with just a hint of roast/smokiness to it.  The flavor is malt with just a bit of roast, toasted bread, with just a hint of brown sugar sweetness.  Mild bitterness at the end finishes this beer off nicely.  Medium bodied.  I could drink this Märzen all day, very nice.

20100926 tap at Wilmington. Darker appearance for a marzen with creamy, sticky beige head. Soft pretzel and raisin aroma with a mild leafiness.  A bit on the sweet side but plenty drinkable and hardly too sweet. Decently done, if only above average, but well above average for a brewpub Oktoberfest.

On tap at West Chester location. Beautiful amber pour. Nice grassy hop nose with some nutty malt aromas. Taste is thin and a bit rough on the edges. Slightly oily but a full malt flavor combines with a moderate carbonation level. Very doughy and a decent session beer.

Draught at Phoenixville BrewPub (at 7.7%ABV):  Aroma of malts, malty sweetness, slight maple syrup, and a hint of nuts.  Poured amber in color with a large, rocky, creamy, tan head that lasted throughout.  Very good lacing.  Clear.  Sparkling.  Lightly sweet, slightly bitter, flavor.  Tastes of malts, , earth, light nuts, and dried leaves.  Medium body.  Lightly dry, slightly syrupy texture.  Average carbonation.  Malt and dry leaf finish is lightly dry.  7.7%ABV is totally hidden.  A nice Oktoberfest.

on tap @Maple Shade-pours a light tan head with amber color.  Aroma is light/medium malt-slight bready, nutty, some fruit/spice hops.  Taste is light/medium malt-slight bready, nutty, some fruit/spice hops.

Draft at Maple Shade. Poured a clear orange/amber with a smaller quickly and totally disipating white head. Aroma had notes of grain, spice and nutts. Flavor was mostly amber malt with light spice, cereal and biscuit. Solid beer that is easily sessionable.
Clear copper color with no head.  Aroma of roasted malts, caramel, and some floral.  Flavor of caramel, roasted malts, bread, and bit of hops.
On tap at Wilmington waterfront.  Appearance is dark mahogany with a medium tan head.  Aroma and taste are very solid - roasted malt, more robust than the average Oktoberfest.

Hand=bottled bomber courtesy Ty5592! Pours clear dark orange with a thick and lacy off-white head. Aroma of caramel, bread, floral hops. Medium body and full carbonation. The lightly sweet caramel, bread, floral hops come through in the taste, along with a little citrus. Dry floral finish. A little more hoppy than the average Marzen, but not so much that it detracts from the malty goodness of the style.
Tap@WestChester.  Largely tasteless, even for the style.  No kick at all.  Not a fan.
Growler courtesy of JB175.  Pours copper with a thin white head.  Smells of caramel, light spice, some pepper.  Tastes of caramel, spice, some sweet hints and a touch of vanilla.  Excellent!
On tap at the newark location. Color was dark brown. Taste was a sweet, malty beer but still balanced. Average texture and carbonation. I enjoyed this beer and would definetly get another!

Too much alcohol (gasp!) It’s 7.7% in Phoenixville.  The alchohol overpowers and it’s very sweet, too sweet for an Oktoberfest in my book.  Nice aroma, spicy, a little yeasty - first sip takes you by surprise.
Golden color with a moderate head.  Sweet, cereal, malty-aroma with some light hops.  Flavor is malty with some light sugar, cereal, and spice.  Solid fest-brew.

[Phoenixville, PA] Poured a copper color with a small, off white head that left light lacing on the glass.  Aroma of nuts, caramel, toast, toffee, and a bit of citrus.  Taste of nuts, toasted dough, caramel, and a rather bitter, dry finish.

On tap at Wilmington location:  Dark copper head, smallish head and lacing.  Caramal malty base with pretty large floral hop base.  More hoppy than your typical oktoberfest.  Crisp and refreshing with a firm kick.  Mild to high carbonation.  I liked it.

On tap at Iron Hill Newark. Poured a nice clear copper color with nice tan foamy head. Aroma was not very strong, mild spice, nuts and malts. Flavor was also mild with hints of bread, spice, and floral taste. Finished crisp and clean with no traces of alcohol, a decent oktoberfest by Iron Hill.

On draft at the North Wales location.  Pours a clear coppery amber with a medium sized beige head.  Aroma of nuts, light fruit and hops.  Taste is hoppy with hints of nuts and light grains.  Hoppier than most Octoberfests.

KSBF 07 (this was brewed at the Newark location)  I think Justin is thier brewer there, and judging by this beer, he rocks.  This is the best Oktoberfest I have had this year, and maybe even better than Ramsteins.  Pours a nice clear orangy amber with nice subtle carbonation and a large frothy long lasting off white head- good lace.  Aroma is fresh baked bread, toasted malts, tons of light munich and vienna with light nuts and a subtle fresh floral hop touch.  Awesome full malty flavor with tons of toasted malts, light caramel flavor, but all munich and vienna- no sharp crystal malts used.  Good clean crisp finish with just a touch of hops in the end.  Smooth as hell.  One of the best beers at the fest by far.

North Wales. Ultra-bright, deep golden body with a sudsy white head.  Nutty, sweet malt aroma with mild toast and soft, fruity esters.  Rich Vienna malt flavor with some good nutty and fruity depth.  Woody/earthy hops in the finish with moderate bitterness.  Moderately sweet, but not cloying.  Very sessionable.  One of the better Oktoberfests.  Not dull and trite like some.

Draft  On tap at North Wales.  Pours a nice copper with a decent creamy white head.  Has a malty aroma with hints of citrus hops.  Had a good flavor with touches of bread.  A light duration and a smooth aftertaste.  A very tasty beer.  Had a good palate and was a nice mix.

On tap at the Phoenixville location.  Pours a translucent deep copper with an average creamy off white head that left some lacing.  Aroma of a grainy maltiness, toffee, caramel and a hint of citrus.  Flavor was also very grainy, cereal, nuts, caramel and some hints of hops to keep things interesting.  Nicely done Marzen.

Poured an orange to light brown color with a very nice head that laced great. Excellent showing of carbonation rising to the surface through the translucent beer. The aroma was nil to nothing, very hard to pick up (even the breadiness that their description advertised). The flavor was nice and malty (definitely bready in flavor) with an underlying bitterness that helped keep the finish straight and balanced. Spices were lacking and there was a bubble gum aspect to the flavor up until the aftertaste, where it vanished. Mouthfeel was moderate bodied with definite carbonation. Biggest knock on this one was the absence of spicing in the flavor profile.

On draft at North Wales.  Copper colored with big, creamy white head.  Aroma of malt, toffee, caramel.  The taste and palate were very rich, firm, and complex, with hints of malt, toffee, caramel, nuts, and I swore I could taste a nutmeggy, pumpkin pie essence.  I took a growler of this and a growler of the Harvest Ale to go.  One of my top 20 marzens of all time.
On tap at the 2004 Kennett Square BF. Poured a medium amber color with no head. Malty sweet aroma and tastes. Caramel.

Body is a clear mahogany with no head.  Aroma of caramel and butterscotch.  Flavor is quite bold, with caramel and fall spices filling out the maltiness and a significant hop bite in the finish.  Very tasty.
